# National Register of Historic Places listings in Portland, Oregon  

The **National Register of Historic Places** listings in Portland, Oregon, comprise a curated set of structures, districts, objects, and sites that have been officially recognized for their historical, architectural, or cultural significance within the United States. These properties are identified and evaluated by the **National Park Service** (NPS) under the authority of the **National Historic Preservation Act** of 1966, which established the criteria and process for inclusion on the **National Register** [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places). Portland’s listings reflect the city’s rich urban tapestry, ranging from early‑twentieth‑century bridges and industrial complexes to mid‑century modern residences and vernacular landmarks that together illustrate the region’s evolution from a frontier outpost to a thriving metropolitan hub [1&#93;].

## Locator map  

A locator map depicting five of Portland’s six official quadrants is provided to give geographic context. Clicking any quadrant link transports the reader to the corresponding National Register list for that sector, with the **South Portland** listings cross‑referenced on the **Southwest Portland** list [5&#93;]. The map is embedded using standard Wikipedia cartographic syntax and can be interacted with via OpenStreetMap tools [Map all coordinates using OpenStreetMap](/Map_all_coordinates_using_OpenStreetMap) • **Download coordinates as KML** [Download coordinates as KML](/Download_coordinates_as_KML).

## Overview of the list  

The following table presents the **full set of buildings, structures, objects, sites, or districts** designated on the **National Register of Historic Places** within the municipal boundaries of Portland, Oregon, accompanied by concise descriptive information. The National Register acknowledges places of **national, state, or local historic significance** across the **United States** [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places). Portland’s inventory includes more than **one‑quarter of Oregon’s** total NRHP properties, which exceed **2,000** listings statewide [3&#93;]. While these resources are geographically dispersed throughout all six quadrants, concentrated clusters appear in the **Downtown** and **Southwest Hills** neighborhoods of the **Southwest** quadrant, as well as in the **Northwest District** of the **Northwest** quadrant [2&#93;].

> *Only historic places that lie strictly within Portland’s legal city limits are represented in this list and its four companion lists covering the other quadrants. Sites that fall just outside the municipal border may appear in broader “Portland” locality lists but are excluded here. Although Portland’s jurisdiction technically extends into **Clackamas County** and **Washington County**, every NRHP‑listed property within the city is situated in **Multnomah County** [Clackamas County,_Oregon](/Clackamas_County,_Oregon), [Washington County,_Oregon](/Washington_County,_Oregon), [Multnomah County,_Oregon](/Multnomah_County,_Oregon).*

The inventory is current through the National Park Service’s most recent publications posted on **December 12, 2025** [4&#93;].

## Current listings  

Below is a detailed, numbered enumeration of each individually listed property, complete with its official **Name on the Register**, an associated **Image**, the **Date listed**, and a brief **Location** and **Description**. Each entry preserves all original internal links, citation markers, and coordinate notations exactly as they appeared in the source material.

1. **[Broadway Bridge](/Broadway_Bridge_(Portland))**  
   *More images*  
   **Date listed:** November 14, 2012 [&#93;]  
   **Location:** Spanning the **[Willamette River](/Willamette_River)** at river mile 11.7, coordinates 45°31′55″N 122°40′26″W / 45.531816°N 122.673898°W / 45.531816; ‑122.673898 [&#93;]  
   **Description:** This is the largest extant example of a **Rall‑type bascule bridge** [Bascule_bridge](/Bascule_bridge) in the United States, and one of only three such designs still standing. Completed in 1913, it marked a pivotal moment in Portland’s **transportation system** development, serving as the city’s first Willamette River crossing built on a wholly new alignment during the twentieth century [7&#93;].

