35. **[John Yeon Speculative House](/John_Yeon_Speculative_House)**  
    **Date listed:** August 1, 2007 [&#93;]  
    **Location:** 3922 N Lombard Street, coordinates 45°34′37″N 122°42′27″W / 45.5769°N 122.7076°W / 45.5769; ‑122.7076 [&#93;]  
    **Description:** One of a series of speculative houses by native Oregon architect and conservationist **[John Yeon](/John_Yeon)** following the critically acclaimed **[Watzek House](/Watzek_House)** (1937). The series included nine houses built between 1938 and 1940 in **Lake Oswego** and Portland. These homes employed a modular design concept that pioneered the use of external plywood as a building material and separate ventilation louvers, allowing for fixed pane glass to be inset between vertical mullions. Yeon is frequently cited as one of the originators of what became known as the **Northwest Regional style of architecture** [91&#93;].  

